---
import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';

const title = 'Getting to Nosara, Costa Rica';
const description =
  'The honest, current way to reach Nosara from anywhere in North America: Liberia versus San José airports, the Sansa shortcut, road conditions, and the transfer we book most often.';
const updated = 'May 2026';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Should I fly into Liberia (LIR) or San José (SJO)?',
    a: 'For Nosara, Liberia (LIR) is almost always the right answer. The drive to Nosara is roughly 2.5 hours of mostly paved road, versus 5 to 5.5 hours from San José over a longer and more variable route. The only common exception is when your home-airport pricing or schedule out of San José is dramatically better.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How long is the Sansa flight from Liberia to Nosara?',
    a: 'The Sansa Airlines flight is about 30 minutes, gate to gate. The luggage allowance is strict (roughly 30 lbs per passenger, including carry-on), so we typically use it for adults traveling light or for guests who want to minimize travel time.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is a 4x4 required to get to Nosara?',
    a: 'A 4x4 SUV is strongly recommended. The last stretch into Nosara is unpaved, and rainy-season conditions can be rough. For visitors staying inside the villa for most of the trip and only moving between Guiones, Pelada, and Garza, a transferred arrival plus a golf cart often beats renting a full SUV.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I rent a car at the Nosara airstrip?',
    a: 'Not really. Nosara has local rental partners that meet you in town, not at the airstrip. The setup we book most often is a Sansa flight in, a transfer to the villa, and golf-cart or SUV rental from Limo Dan delivered to the property.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Are there direct flights from the US to Liberia (LIR)?',
    a: 'Yes. Liberia (LIR) is served year-round by direct flights from a number of US hubs including Los Angeles, Dallas, Houston, Miami, New York, Atlanta, and Charlotte, with seasonal lifts from additional cities. Schedules and carriers shift season to season, so check at booking.',
  },
];

const pageSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'Article',
      headline: title,
      description,
      datePublished: '2026-05-18',
      dateModified: '2026-05-18',
      author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Avela Travel' },
      publisher: {
        '@type': 'Organization',
        name: 'Avela Travel',
        logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://avela.travel/images/avela-logo.png' },
      },
      mainEntityOfPage: 'https://avela.travel/guides/getting-to-nosara',
      image: 'https://avela.travel/images/nosara/pink-island.jpg',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: f.q,
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a },
      })),
    },
  ],
};

const related = [
  { slug: 'when-to-visit', title: 'When to visit Nosara', category: 'Seasons' },
  { slug: 'what-to-pack', title: 'What to pack for Nosara', category: 'Logistics' },
  { slug: 'eating-in-nosara', title: 'Eating in Nosara', category: 'Food' },
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  category="Logistics"
  readTime="5 min read"
  heroImage="/images/nosara/pink-island.jpg"
  heroImageAlt="Aerial view of a Nosara beach with turquoise water and sandy coves"
  updated={updated}
  pageSchema={pageSchema}
  related={related}
>
  <p>
    Nosara sits on the southern tip of the Nicoya Peninsula, on Costa Rica's
    Pacific coast. It is remote on purpose. There is no big highway in, no
    chain hotel on the beach, and the last stretch of road still kicks up
    dust. That setup is exactly what protects the place. It also means
    arriving here takes a little planning.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is how we route every Avela guest, and what we would tell a friend
    booking their first trip.
  </p>

  <h2>The short version</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fly into Liberia (LIR), not San José.</strong> The drive is half the time and the road is almost entirely paved.</li>
    <li><strong>From LIR you have two routes:</strong> a private ground transfer (around 2.5 hours) or a 30-minute Sansa flight into the Nosara airstrip.</li>
    <li><strong>You do not need a rental car to enjoy Nosara,</strong> but if you want to roam Pelada, Garza, and the jungle roads, a 4x4 SUV or a golf cart helps.</li>
    <li><strong>Book transfers ahead.</strong> We use Terratour Shuttles as our transport partner. Their drivers know the road and the villas.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Liberia (LIR) vs San José (SJO)</h2>
  <p>
    Daniel Oduber International Airport in Liberia is the closer of Costa
    Rica's two international airports and the one purpose-built for
    Guanacaste. The drive from Liberia to Nosara is roughly 2.5 hours and
    is paved the entire way until you turn off the main highway near
    Nicoya.
  </p>
  <p>
    San José (Juan Santamaría, SJO) is Costa Rica's bigger hub. It is
    further inland and the drive to Nosara runs 5 to 5.5 hours over a
    longer, less direct route. Unless your home-airport pricing or
    schedule is dramatically better out of SJO, fly into LIR.
  </p>
  <div class="guide-pull">
    Ninety-five percent of the time, Liberia is the right answer for
    Nosara. We can count the SJO exceptions on one hand.
  </div>

  <h2>The Sansa shortcut</h2>
  <p>
    Sansa Airlines is Costa Rica's domestic carrier. They run multiple
    daily flights between Liberia and Nosara on small Cessna Caravans,
    and the flight is roughly 30 minutes.
  </p>
  <p>
    The plus side is obvious: instead of a 2.5-hour drive after an
    international flight, you land in Nosara in time for lunch. The view
    of the Pacific coastline coming in is also part of the trip.
  </p>
  <p>
    The catch is the luggage allowance. Sansa flights carry a strict
    weight limit, typically around 30 lbs (14 kg) per passenger including
    your carry-on. Surfboards, golf clubs, and overstuffed suitcases
    often need to come by ground transfer separately. We routinely split
    parties: adults fly Sansa, while a transfer brings boards and
    oversize luggage to meet you at the villa.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Nosara airstrip is a single runway with a small open-air terminal
    on the edge of town. Your villa is rarely more than a 10-minute drive
    from arrival.
  </p>

  <h2>Ground transfers from Liberia</h2>
  <p>
    Driving from Liberia is the simplest option for most guests. The
    route runs south on Route 21 to Nicoya, then west toward the coast.
    Expect roughly 2.5 hours door to door. The last 15 to 20 minutes is
    on unpaved road as you approach Nosara.
  </p>
  <p>
    We book ground transfers through <strong>Terratour Shuttles</strong>,
    our local transport partner. Their drivers know which villas have
    tight driveways, which routes are passable in green season, and
    where to make the standard halfway stop for coffee or bathrooms.
    For families with kids, they bring proper car seats on request.
  </p>
  <p>
    Standard family-size SUVs seat up to six with luggage. Larger
    groups get a Sprinter-style van. We typically arrange one return
    transfer with a relaxed lunch stop on the way back to LIR so no one
    is hungry and rushing to clear customs.
  </p>

  <h2>Renting a car (or not)</h2>
  <p>
    Whether you need a rental car depends entirely on what you want to
    do once you arrive.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>If you are mostly going to be in Guiones,</strong> walking to
    surf, eating at restaurants within 5 to 10 minutes of your villa,
    you do not need a rental car. A golf cart is faster, easier, and
    more fun.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>If you want range,</strong> sunset dinners up the hill at
    Coyol, dawn drives to Ostional, an ATV day in the back hills, a
    proper SUV makes the week easier. We work with <strong>Limo Dan</strong>{' '}
    for car and golf-cart rentals delivered directly to your villa, and
    with <strong>Pipin's Rentals</strong> for ATVs and side-by-sides.
  </p>
  <p>
    A 4x4 is strongly recommended even in dry season. Some of the most
    interesting drives in this area, the road up to Coyol, the back
    route to the waterfalls, the Ostional turtle road, get rough fast.
  </p>

  <h2>Road conditions, season by season</h2>
  <h3>Dry season (December to April)</h3>
  <p>
    Roads are dusty but consistently passable. Even the unpaved stretches
    are manageable in a standard SUV. Driving at sunset is when the dust
    is heaviest, so leave a buffer for visibility.
  </p>
  <h3>Green season (May to November)</h3>
  <p>
    Afternoon rains can briefly flood low river crossings. A 4x4 makes
    the difference. Most days the rain hits in the late afternoon and
    clears overnight, so morning drives are usually fine. October is
    the wettest month of the year on this coast, and a few side roads
    become impassable. Your driver or villa host will know which.
  </p>

  <h2>Arrival day, the way we run it</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Land at Liberia (LIR), clear immigration and customs.</li>
    <li>Meet your Terratour driver at the airport exit. They will be holding an Avela sign.</li>
    <li>Drive 2.5 hours toward Nosara. Most drivers offer a halfway stop for coffee, a bathroom, or to stretch.</li>
    <li>Arrive at the villa. Your house manager is there to walk you through the property, hand off keys, and answer questions.</li>
    <li>If you have requested a chef-prepared welcome meal, that is plated and ready.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    On departure day, we reverse the order, with a relaxed lunch stop
    built into the drive so no one is rushed at the airport.
  </p>

  <h2>What about visas and entry?</h2>
  <p>
    Visitors from the US, Canada, the UK, the EU, Australia, and most of
    Latin America do not need a visa for tourist stays in Costa Rica up
    to 180 days. You need a passport valid for at least one day after
    your planned departure, and proof of onward travel (your return
    ticket). Always check official sources for current requirements
    before flying, since rules change.
  </p>

  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
  <div class="guide-faq">
    {faqs.map((f) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{f.q}</summary>
        <p>{f.a}</p>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="guide-callout">
    <p>
      Booking with us? We coordinate every step of arrival: flight timing,
      transfer scheduling, rental delivery to the villa, and a welcome
      contact who meets you at the door. Nothing to figure out on landing.
    </p>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>
